via the militarization of police, securitized housing developments, and ineffectual counterterrorism efforts. But more than just an exposé of the nefarious corporations, corrupt agencies, and incompetent governments, this book uniquely shines the spotlight on the ordinary citizens whose desires for safety drive these phenomena. Angela Davis has written of the challenge of persuading people that "safety, safeguarded by violence, is not really safety." Maguire and Low aid us in thinking through the challenge, providing a common language to discuss security capitalism and offering ways to escape its clutches.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aInternal securityxSocial aspects. 0aPolicexSocial aspects. 0aPrivate security servicesxSocial aspects. 0aSecurity sectorxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  acapitalism.  acounterterrorism.  afear.  agated communities.  ahomeland security.  apolicing.  aprivate urban development.  asecurity capitalism.  asecurity.1 aLow, Setha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363920140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503639201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503639201/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles